Because epinephrine and dopamine are vasoconstrictors as well as chronotropes, healthcare providers must assess the patient's intravascular volume status and avoid hypovolemia when using these drugs.
Dobutamine (a $\beta$-adrenergic agonist) is appropriate when vasoconstriction is not desired.

Either epinephrine infusions or dopamine infusions may be used for patients with stable bradycardia, particularly if associated with hypotension, for whom atropine may be inappropriate or after atropine fails.

Begin epinephrine infusion at a dose of 2 to $10 \mathrm{mcg} / \mathrm{min}$ and titrate to patient response; begin dopamine infusion at 5 to $20 \mathrm{mcg} / \mathrm{kg}$ per minute and titrate to patient response. At lower doses, dopamine has a more selective effect on inotropy and heart rate; at higher doses (greater than 10 mcg/kg per minute infusion), it also has vasoconstrictive effects.

