- For any advanced airway device, the ventilation rate is once every 6 seconds for respiratory or cardiac arrest.
- We do not recommend the routine use of cricoid pressure in cardiac arrest. Although cricoid pressure in nonarrest patients may protect the airway from aspiration and gastric insufflation during bag-mask ventilation, it also may impede ventilation and interfere with placing a tube or supraglottic airway.

