\section*{Glossary}

This table defines some common terms used in ACLS.

\begin{tabular}{|l|l|}
\hline \multicolumn{2}{|c|}{A} \\
\hline Acute & Having a sudden onset and short course \\
\hline Acute myocardial infarction (AMI) & The early critical stage of necrosis of heart muscle tissue caused by blockage of a coronary artery \\
\hline Advanced cardiovascular life support (ACLS) & Emergency medical procedures in which basic life support efforts of CPR are supplemented with drug administration, IV fluids, etc \\
\hline Asystole & Absence of electrical and mechanical activity in the heart \\
\hline Atrial fibrillation & In atrial fibrillation the atria "quiver" chaotically and the ventricles beat irregularly \\
\hline Atrial flutter & Rapid, irregular atrial contractions due to an abnormality of atrial excitation \\
\hline Atrioventricular (AV) block & A delay in the normal flow of electrical impulses that cause the heart to beat \\
\hline Automated external defibrillator (AED) & A portable device used to restart a heart that has stopped \\
\hline & B \\
\hline Basic life support (BLS) & Emergency treatment of a victim of cardiac or respiratory arrest through cardiopulmonary resuscitation and emergency cardiovascular care \\
\hline Bradycardia & Slow heart rate, whether physiologically or pathologically \\
\hline \multicolumn{2}{|c|}{C} \\
\hline Capnography & The measurement and graphic display of $\mathrm{CO}_{2}$ levels in the airways, which can be performed by infrared spectroscopy \\
\hline Cardiac arrest & Temporary or permanent cessation of the heartbeat \\
\hline Cardiopulmonary resuscitation (CPR) & A basic emergency procedure for life support, consisting of mainly manual external cardiac massage and some artificial respiration \\
\hline Coronary syndrome & A group of clinical symptoms compatible with acute myocardial ischemia. Also called coronary heart disease. \\
\hline Coronary thrombosis & The blocking of the coronary artery of the heart by a thrombus \\
\hline
\end{tabular}

\begin{tabular}{|l|l|}
\hline \multicolumn{2}{|c|}{E} \\
\hline Electrocardiogram (ECG) & A test that provides a typical record of normal heart action \\
\hline Endotracheal (ET) intubation & The passage of a tube through the nose or mouth into the trachea for maintenance of the airway \\
\hline Esophageal-tracheal tube & A double-lumen tube with inflatable balloon cuffs that seal off the hypopharynx from the oropharynx and esophagus; used for airway management \\
\hline \multicolumn{2}{|c|}{H} \\
\hline Hydrogen ion (acidosis) & The accumulation of acid and hydrogen ions or depletion of the alkaline reserve (bicarbonate content) in the blood and body tissues, decreasing the pH \\
\hline Hyperkalemia & An abnormally high concentration of potassium ions in the blood. Also called hyperpotassemia. \\
\hline Hypoglycemia & An abnormally low concentration of glucose in the blood \\
\hline Hypokalemia & An abnormally low concentration of potassium ions in the blood. Also called hypopotassemia. \\
\hline Hypothermia & When the patient's core body temperature is below $96.8^{\circ} \mathrm{F}$ ( $36^{\circ} \mathrm{C}$ ) \\
\hline Hypovolemia & A decrease in the volume of circulating blood \\
\hline Hypoxia & A deficiency of oxygen reaching the tissues of the body \\
\hline \multicolumn{2}{|c|}{1} \\
\hline Intraosseous (IO) & Within a bone \\
\hline Intravenous (IV) & Within a vein \\
\hline \multicolumn{2}{|c|}{M} \\
\hline Mild hypothermia & When the patient's core body temperature is between $93.2^{\circ} \mathrm{F}$ and $96.8^{\circ} \mathrm{F}$ \\
\hline Moderate hypothermia & When the patient's core body temperature is from $86^{\circ} \mathrm{F}$ and $93.2^{\circ} \mathrm{F}$ \\
\hline \multicolumn{2}{|c|}{N} \\
\hline Nasopharyngeal (NPA) & Pertaining to the nose and pharynx \\
\hline
\end{tabular}

\begin{tabular}{|l|l|}
\hline \multicolumn{2}{|c|}{0} \\
\hline Oropharyngeal airway (OPA) & A tube used to provide free passage of air between the mouth and pharynx \\
\hline \multicolumn{2}{|c|}{P} \\
\hline Perfusion & The passage of fluid (such as blood) through a specific organ or area of the body (such as the heart) \\
\hline Prophylaxis & Prevention of or protection against disease \\
\hline Pulmonary edema & A condition in which fluid accumulates in the lungs \\
\hline Pulseless electrical activity (PEA) & Continued electrical rhythmicity of the heart in the absence of effective mechanical function \\
\hline \multicolumn{2}{|c|}{R} \\
\hline Recombinant tissue plasminogen activator (rtPA) & A clot-dissolving substance produced naturally by cells in the walls of blood vessels \\
\hline \multicolumn{2}{|c|}{S} \\
\hline Severe hypothermia & When the patient's core body temperature is below $86^{\circ} \mathrm{F}$ \\
\hline Sinus rhythm & The rhythm of the heart produced by impulses from the sinoatrial node \\
\hline Supraglottic & Situated or occurring above the glottis \\
\hline Synchronized cardioversion & Uses a sensor to deliver a shock that is synchronized with a peak in the QRS complex \\
\hline Syncope & A loss of consciousness over a short period of time, caused by a temporary lack of oxygen in the brain \\
\hline \multicolumn{2}{|c|}{T} \\
\hline Tachycardia & Increased heart rate, usually $\geq 100 / \mathrm{min}$ \\
\hline Tamponade (cardiac) & A condition caused by accumulation of fluid between the heart and the pericardium, resulting in excess pressure on the heart. This impairs the heart's ability to pump sufficient blood. \\
\hline Tension pneumothorax & Pneumothorax resulting from a wound in the chest wall which acts as a valve that permits air to enter the pleural cavity but prevents its escape \\
\hline
\end{tabular}

\begin{tabular}{|l|l|}
\hline Thrombus & A blood clot formed within a blood vessel \\
\hline \multicolumn{2}{|c|}{U} \\
\hline Unsynchronized shock & An electrical shock that will be delivered as soon as the operator pushes the shock button to discharge the defibrillator. Thus, the shock can fall anywhere within the cardiac cycle. \\
\hline \multicolumn{2}{|c|}{V} \\
\hline Ventricular fibrillation (VF) & Very rapid uncoordinated fluttering contractions of the ventricles \\
\hline Ventricular tachycardia (VT) & A rapid heart rate that originates in one of the lower chambers (ventricles) of the heart \\
